MALAYSIA DAYBOOK: Maxis 610 Million-Ringgit Net Beats Estimates

-- B y   B a r r y   P o r t e r
-- 
2011-02-28T21:16:34Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-28/malaysia-daybook-maxis-610-million-ringgit-net-beats-estimates.html
  Maxis Bhd .,  Malaysia ’s biggest
mobile-phone operator, reported fourth-quarter net income of 610
million ringgit ($200 million), or 8.1 sen per share, beating
analysts’ estimates. The Kuala Lumpur-based company, controlled
by billionaire T. Ananda Krishnan, proposed a final dividend of
16 sen a share, bringing its total payout for the year to 40 sen.  Maxis was expected to record a profit of 596.2 million
ringgit for the three months ended Dec. 31, according to the
median of five analysts’ forecasts in a survey by Bloomberg News.  MARKETS:
* Malaysia’s FTSE Bursa Malaysia KLCI Index rose 0.1 percent.
* The MSCI Asia Pacific Index increased 0.5 percent.
* The  Dow Jones Industrial Average  gained 0.8 percent.
* Palm oil May-delivery futures fell 1.2 percent to 3,472
ringgit a metric ton.  EQUITY PREVIEW:
* EON Capital Bhd. (EON MK): The Malaysian banking group said
fourth-quarter net income jumped 64 percent from a year earlier
to 100.9 million ringgit on higher revenue.
* K&N Kenanga Holdings Bhd. (KNK MK): The  investment banking  and
stock-broking group said it had a loss of 29.7 million ringgit
in the fourth quarter compared with a profit of 9.75 million
ringgit a year earlier because of impairment charges on a loan
and an investment in an associate company.
* Kencana Petroleum Bhd. (KEPB): The oil and gas services
company said it won a 115 million-ringgit contract from the
local arm of U.K.-based Petrofac Ltd.
* Kurnia Asia Bhd. (KUAB MK): The Malaysian insurer said it had
a net loss of 8.52 million ringgit in the fourth quarter
compared with a profit of 10.9 million ringgit a year earlier.
* Lion Industries Corp. (LLB MK): The Malaysian maker of steel
bars and wire rods said second-quarter net income jumped to
142.8 million ringgit from 83.5 million ringgit a year ago on
higher sales.
* PPB Group Bhd. (PEP MK): The company controlled by billionaire  Robert Kuok  said fourth-quarter net income more than halved to
152.7 million ringgit, partly due to lower contributions from
its Singapore commodities-trading associate Wilmar International
Ltd.
* Xidelang Holdings Ltd. (XIDE MK): The Chinese maker of
footwear products said fourth-quarter net income doubled from a
year earlier to 20.3 million ringgit as sales surged.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
